:INFO
The Memoir That Is Honest About Ambivalence
Most memoirs about difficult childhoods resolve into gratitude or condemnation. \
The Glass Castle does neither. Jeannette Walls writes about her father Rex with \
genuine love and genuine fury at the same time, and she does not resolve that \
tension because it has not resolved. Her parents were charismatic, brilliant, \
reckless, and negligent, and she understood all of those things simultaneously. \
That honesty is what makes the book important and also what makes it uncomfortable.

:NOW
Still thinking about which parent is harder to understand

:QUOTE [subtitle:Jeannette Walls, quotetype:PLAIN]
No child is responsible for the choices her parents make for her.

:JOURNEY
Reading The Glass Castle
Section
Impact
- Welch WV section | 5 | Most visceral | The most specific poverty I have read
- Rex Walls chapters | 4 | Complicated love | Harder to write than condemnation
- New York section | 4 | Peak ambivalence | Most uncomfortable section of the book
- Final chapters | 5 | Refuses resolution | More honest for refusing an easy ending

:NOTE
The book asks something difficult of the reader: to hold love and anger about the \
same people at the same time. It does not let you pick one side and stay there.

